  Assignment
Problem Statement:

Design an Electronic Health Records System to manage patient records, clinical encounters, test results, prescriptions, allergies, and vaccination history. Focus on data security, integrity, and quick access to longitudinal patient data.

ðŸ“ Schema Design

Main Tables:
â€¢ Patients (Patient_ID, Name, DOB, Gender, Contact, Address, Blood_Type, Insurance_ID)
â€¢ Visits (Visit_ID, Patient_ID, Visit_Date, Doctor_ID, Reason, Notes)
â€¢ Lab_Results (Result_ID, Visit_ID, Test_Name, Result_Value, Normal_Range, Test_Date)
â€¢ Prescriptions (Prescription_ID, Visit_ID, Medicine_ID, Dosage, Frequency, Start_Date, End_Date)
â€¢ Allergies (Allergy_ID, Patient_ID, Allergen, Severity, Notes)
â€¢ Vaccinations (Vaccine_ID, Patient_ID, Vaccine_Name, Dose_Number, Administered_Date)

Reference Tables:
â€¢ Insurance_Providers (Insurance_ID, Name, Coverage)
â€¢ Medications (Medicine_ID, Name, Type, Manufacturer)

âœ… SQL Queries:

â€¢ Patients with abnormal lab results in the last 3 months.
â€¢ List of medications prescribed by each doctor.
â€¢ Patients with known allergies to prescribed medications.
â€¢ Vaccination history for patients under age 12.
â€¢ Patients missing required vaccinations.
â€¢ Lab test trends (e.g., increasing cholesterol over time).

âœ… PL/SQL Logic:

â€¢ Procedure to add a lab result with validation.
â€¢ Trigger to prevent duplicate allergy records.
â€¢ Function to retrieve patient summary (diagnoses, meds, labs).
â€¢ Exception handling for invalid dosage or test inputs.

âœ… Performance:

â€¢ Index on Patient_ID, Visit_Date, Test_Name
â€¢ Partition Lab_Results by year
â€¢ Materialized view for patient history snapshot

Expected Outcome:
âœ” Well-designed relational database schema with normalized tables.
âœ” Efficient SQL queries covering real-world e-commerce scenarios.
âœ” PL/SQL procedures, triggers, and exception handling for business logic implementation.
âœ” Performance optimization techniques applied for improved query execution.
âœ” Clean, well-documented SQL scripts.
ðŸ“… Submission Guidelines:
ðŸ“Œ Submit a SQL script file (.sql) containing:
Table creation scripts.
Data insertion scripts.
SQL queries with their expected outputs.
ðŸ“Œ Submit a PL/SQL script file (.sql) containing:
Procedures, functions, and triggers.
ðŸ“Œ Submit a Performance Report (PDF/Word) explaining:
Query optimization techniques used.
Indexing and partitioning strategies.
Any performance improvements applied.
